       HHttaaggss generates a hypertext from a set of source files  of
       C, C++, Yacc, Java, PHP and Assembly.

       In  advance  of  using  this  command,  you should execute
       ggttaaggss(1) in the root directory of a source project.   Then
       you  can  execute  hhttaaggss in the same place.  HHttaaggss makes a
       directory named 'HTML', and puts a hypertext in  it.   You
       can start browsing at 'HTML/index.html'.

       Since hhttaaggss generates a static hypertext as long as the --DD
       or --ff option is not specified, you can  move  it  anywhere
       and browse it by any browser without any HTTP server.

       This  command  has  so  many  options.   If you are new on
       hhttaaggss, it is recommended  to  use  the  ----ssuuggggeesstt  option.
       With  that option, hhttaaggss chooses popular options on behalf
       of you.

